### Summary (w/c 20.10.2025)

**Promising OV growth in W8 (+16% WoW), likely driven by:**

* Marketing: Impact of activity continuing to build; growth social activity launched on 22/10; continued CRM optimisation  
* In-app experience changes: Re-instatement of braze marketing pop up and home carousel pinned at position 1; addition of FD metadata onto bottom sheet (lower impact)

[***Proposition Performance:***](#bookmark=id.8jy7lqj4zkht) No major changes in proposition performance vs previous weeks. 

* Ordering patterns and top brands, cuisines and dishes continue to remain constant  
* Cx composition also mirrors previous weeks, with a similar LBDS and regional split, and continued over-indexing among high-frequency customers  
* From a cx behaviour perspective, initial funnel insights are helping us pinpoint where cx drop off, and identify actions to address these gaps (deep-dive from this morning [here](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1jmpXZ6y17sr5Lc2UvOKgQ7M6rNcUBI5zBynho-z9pbs/edit?slide=id.g307ea4a988d_0_903#slide=id.g307ea4a988d_0_903), summary of insights and potential implications [below](#bookmark=id.yueitjg58ltu))   
* Ratings are down WoW (4.27 down from 4.44) with more 1\* orders (11% vs 6%) and fewer 5\* orders (70% vs 74%)

[***Marketing:***](#bookmark=id.e47f0rcxdspk) 

**Media Insights:** Growth social activity launched on 22/10 and we are now live across all planned channels, with next burst of OOH activity going live from 3rd-16th November. Discussions underway to revisit and upweight three specific channels further in Q4: OOH, Press (revisit opportunity), and Mid-Tier Influencers, as walked through in today‚Äôs Cx Funnel session with further exploration into the rephasing of underspend in promo.

**DXGY:** 6.2k Cx have entered in total, 11% of those have placed their second order with 156 Cx completing all steps. To date, ¬£3,900 vouchers have been earned, with spend at ¬£1,140 (vs total budget ¬£1m). Given underpacing in spend we‚Äôve investigated an

**CRM:** This week, we launched the Family Time value proposition email to all Cx. We observed the highest conversion to order from push, with 68 customers ordering after receiving the push (vs. an average of \~20 orders). The email CTR was 0.3%, consistent with previous sends and in line with benchmark. Evolving CRM strategy, we are including two Px solus emails before the end of the year to highlight the value proposition to Cx ([plan until EoY](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1eiWAcwP1mJ7eV9R-cw0CcxYJ2f_4i7YGR3r52oKUuyI/edit?slide=id.g38d92ef2810_0_4#slide=id.g38d92ef2810_0_4)) and are looking to rerun ‚Äòday of week‚Äô experiment due to CTR reporting issues raised last WRB.

[***Operations Performance***](#bookmark=id.xaawvvkuqgme) ***and [Care:](#bookmark=id.2bly6deyk5rk)*** Slight improvements in service metrics, but similar challenges persist

**B10s:** 

* B10s continue to be elevated vs. Non-Dinneroo mealtimes; this is being driven by unacceptable lates increasing \-3.34 ppt WoW to 9.98%, RWT remaining stable at 7.7% (+0.1ppt WoW), however still \+2.9ppt higher than benchmark (4.6%)  
* While OI improved \-0.37ppt WoW to 3.0%, we are seeing spillages and crushed packaging as the \#1 recurring issue (45 instances) ‚Äî particularly for Wagamama, Dishoom, and Pho. Wrong items and improper cooking follow as the next most common complaint types. We have looked into this at brand level, this has also been shared with AMs for immediate action.  
* Our primary offenders across the three key B10 metrics are: wagamama, Pho, Dishoom, PEX and Bella Italia. These brands continue to be focused on in weekly Operating Theatre touchpoints.

**Care:**

* **Claims:** declined vs prior week at 6.73% orders with a claim (+0.18 ppt WoW) and average claim amount at ¬£14.55 (+53p WoW), reflecting poorer operational performance, with Missing Items remaining the top offender for CCPO at 22p, while Unacceptable Lates also increased to 2.71%.  
* **OTP: 46p per Dinneroo order** (+28p WoW), which is **\+36p above [target](https://docs.google.com/document/u/0/d/1VI8MI8jZlmiXNNKKB_cWaeiW9eH3rQ-LK4Gbrv_FJsw/edit)** (10p) and **\+25p above budget** (21p). 

### 1\. Proposition Performance

OV grew 16% WoW to 4.6k orders. 

|  | 01/09/2025 | 08/09/2025 | 15/09/2025 | 22/09/2025 | 29/09/2025 | 06/10/2025 | 13/10/2025 | 20/10/2025 |
| :---- | ----: | ----: | ----: | ----: | ----: | ----: | ----: | ----: |
| OV | 1,807 | 2,390 | 2,692 | 2,965 | 3,546 | 3,602 | 3,928 | 4,610 |
| ATV | ¬£34.57 | ¬£34.27 | ¬£34.13 | ¬£33.51 | ¬£33.99 | ¬£33.69 | ¬£33.71 | ¬£33.76 |
| GTV | ¬£62,474.91 | ¬£81,902.88 | ¬£91,887.17 | ¬£99,367.01 | ¬£120,530.83 | ¬£121,360.52 | ¬£132,400.52 | ¬£155,638 |

* **Order Composition**  
  * **Ordering patterns:** Similar trends as in previous week on ASAP vs scheduling and time of order; ASAP continues to make up around one-fifth of orders, albeit decrease WoW (to 17% vs 20% last week, 17% W1-7).  
  * **Top performing brands, cuisines, dishes:** Minimal change \- top 5 brands remain the same (Pho, Wags, Dishoom, PEX, Banana Tree); Asian continues to dominate; top 3 dishes remain the same (Wags Family Chicken Katsu, Pho‚Äôs Pho the Whole Family and Dishoom‚Äôs Chicken Ruby).  
  * **Basket make-up:** 63% of cx are adding an additional main to their purchase.  
  * **Anecdotal changes:** Banana Tree has taken onboard Cx feedback regarding two of their dishes (Katsu Curry and Chicken Curry), improving portion size and slightly altering recipe to adjust for children's taste. Changes to be implemented next week.  
* **Cx Composition**  
  * **Family split:** LBDS split continues to sit at c.20%.  
  * **Cx-type (existing and frequent):**  99% of FTT cx are existing-to-platform. 67% have PLUS and 61% return to Roo within 7 days of making an FTT purchase.  
  * **Location:** Similar to previous weeks, with FTT OV composition by region closely aligns to total Roo GTV composition by region.  
* **Cx Behaviour**  
  * **See cx funnel slides [here](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1jmpXZ6y17sr5Lc2UvOKgQ7M6rNcUBI5zBynho-z9pbs/edit).** Early insights  
    * Only c.50% are entering via in-app entry points; c.50% come from other sources (e.g. px menus, CRM etc.). ***Implications:*** (i) If non in-app entry points are proving popular, it may be beneficial to explore ways to accelerate these even further (e.g. px feature FTT items as hero images on their menu; more affiliate links) (ii) Additional benefit from accelerating supply expansion (and potentially relaxing the 3+ rx in a zone constraint) if menu is a key entry point (to verify).  
    * In-window FTT cx entering through in-app entry points show lower CvR compared to non-FTT benchmarks. While they over-index on entry ‚Üí view item and add to cart ‚Üí see basket, this is offset by underperformance in view item ‚Üí basket and basket ‚Üí checkout. ***Implications:*** (i) Lower view item ‚Üí basket conversion may reflect: (a) Less intentional browsing as cx are still learning about the proposition \- expected but nevertheless highlighting the need to keep educating cx (b) Limited selection, highlighting the need to improve assortment (ii) The drop from basket ‚Üí checkout could indicate bill shock at checkout, suggesting we may want to review pricing, fees and / or messaging (to verify with research).  
    * Lower conversion for out-of-window purchases. ***Implications:*** (i) More education needed around scheduled orders (ii) Potential scope to trigger interventions (e.g. pop-ups if cx tries to exit after realising they need to schedule, or CRM nudges for cx that did exit out-of-window to alert them that ASAP ordering is now available.   
  * **Ratings:** Drop in ratings WoW \- from 4.27 (vs 4.44 avg W1-7), with  more 1\* orders (11% vs avg W1-7) and fewer 5\* orders (70% vs 74% W1-7).

### 2\. Marketing 

#### A) Media Insights ([Emily Lodge](mailto:emily.burke@deliveroo.co.uk)[Liz Wetz](mailto:liz.wetz@deliveroo.co.uk)[Russell Jackson-Pugh](mailto:russell.pugh@deliveroo.co.uk)) 

### 

* We continue to be live across BVOD (Sky), paid social (Meta & YT) with hero talent, influencer & digital graphic, digital audio, search, affiliates & CRM. Our next burst of OOH activity goes live from 3rd-16th November.  
* Growth social activity went live on 22/10 after alignment in last Friday‚Äôs WBR to set live with standard purchase event given delays in being able to set up Family Time event. This means we are now live across every channel.  
* One theme we are seeing across channels is a slight underpacing due to the geo-targeted nature of the plan (marketing live in FTT zones only). We‚Äôre monitoring the pacing very closely, with potential solutions to pacing challenges being asset consolidation (i.e. fewer assets mean we can focus objectives on reaching unique and repeat customers with one variant vs landing multiple creative variants within the same audience groupings).   
* More detail on specific channel performance can be found in the Marketing Weekly Performance Doc [Family Time Marketing Weekly Performance Update - 16.10-22.10](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Epw1f4xddHHvC1jfIowJ_p3m-0-YAguc9MpMPowMc3I/edit?usp=sharing)  
* In search we are making optimisations to capture more search volume and drive CTR including  
- Match type refinements to stop cannibalisation against brand terms  
- Expanding search terms to include additional generic, dish-related & brand terms  
- Exploring adding site link to brand terms  
* From next week we will be feeding in a question on Family Dinneroo to our Continuous Discovery workstream (weekly customer interview programme) to test unprompted awareness of the proposition  
* We are also working with the Brand Insights team to explore setting up a fortnightly or monthly consumer survey to regularly test unprompted awareness & perceptions of family time  
* We are continuing to work through our proposal for Family Time support in H1 2026

#### C) DXGY Insights  ([Emma Wilson](mailto:emma.wilson@deliveroo.co.uk)[Sheena Kotadia](mailto:sheena.kotadia@deliveroo.co.uk)[Jordan Freedman](mailto:jordan.freedman@deliveroo.co.uk))

Performance continues to pace behind business case assumptions, working with CRM and Product teams to drive improvement. Key Drivers: 6.2k have entered in total, 11% of those have placed their second order with 156 Cx completing all steps. To date, ¬£3,900 vouchers have been earned, with spend at ¬£1,140 (vs total budget ¬£1m).

**Since our last update we have**  
1\. Ireland Audience set up issues: a failure in the table surfacing primary addresses in IRE has meant targeting for cx has not worked, and as a result we have had 3 entrants to the campaign in total.  
2\. Low upper-funnel engagement: less Cx entering the stampcard vs those eligible. 6.2k entered since 6/10 vs 10.1k unique Cx. It was investigating this issue that we noticed Ireland performance was low (the issue above). We have a 20% hold out, plus a gap for the Ireland Cx (confirming, but would be small), leaving an unexplained gap of c.2k.   
3\. In-app journey impacting voucher redemption: The absence of in-app merchandising or clear prompts once customers complete their stampcard could be contributing to low redemption rates \- 29% versus the 85% benchmark.

**Next Steps:**

* CRM to launch an additional ‚Äúlast chance‚Äù push next week, expanding the target audience to increase awareness and participation. Subject lines are being optimised to improve email click-through rates.  
* Proposal to add in-app merch for Cx once they complete all steps, making it clearer that a voucher is available to use and encouraging redemption. Working through with [Natasha Patel](mailto:natasha.patel@deliveroo.co.uk)  
* New campaign being launched for Ireland on Monday, audience of 1.2m, no impact to XP.  
* Discuss the launch of a second UK DXGY after the 4th November entry period ends to scoop more people into the proposition

| OI | 3.0 % (-0.37% WoW) | 1.94% (-0.11ppt‚Äì WoW) | Wagamama 3.81% (22.2%), PizzaExpress 3.59% (11.11%), Bella Italia 10.2% (5.05%) |

This week, Px Ops flagged five partners as a focus within the Px Mobilisation tracker, which were then discussed in detail on the bi-weekly Operating Theatre:


* PizzaExpress:  
  * RWT improved WoW, however still at elevated levels (13.4%). The root cause determined by the partner is menu-item familiarity within the kitchen, and therefore is taking low order sites more time to get used to prepping the items.    
  * OI is also high at 3.59%, and higher than non-dinneroo orders (3 instances of crushed pizza boxes, 1 occurrence during previous week).   
  * Two Px caused cancellations \-  due to item unavailability of Lasagna.  
  * Action plan discussed with Px:   
    * PEX HQ state that sites are underestimating the number of lasagnas that require defrosting (it takes 48 hrs to thaw), and therefore this is causing out of stocks.  AM raised with PEX ops manager who is addressing the offending sites and educating more widely to FTT participating sites.  
    * RWT: PEx‚Äôs Ops team are suggesting that low order volume sites should be allowed to complete test orders to familiarise themselves with the Dinneroo dishes to speed up their prep times and avoid RWT issues  
    * OI data continues to be surfaced with PEX for them to work with sites  
* Pho:  
  * Spilled broths is becoming a new and more consistent complaint. Pho have made positive improvements on missing sides and menu items, such as prawn crackers, but despite good use of packaging, instances of spills are increasing. Discussions have kicked off to review packaging directly with Pho   
* Wagamama:  
  * Cx expectations not matching the offer, inconsistent portion sizes and missing items being driven by add ons,  
  * Actions taken: Wags team reviewing FTT descriptions of items, re-training chefs for portion size to fall in line with cx expectations, GMs and area managers focusing on underperforming sites and areas.  
* Banana Tree & Las Iguanas:  
  * Banana Tree: OI Dinneroo 2.25% vs non-dinneroo 1.73%.   
  * Las Iguanas: RWT Dinneroo 18.60% vs Non-Dinneroo 9.30%  
    Continued strong engagement with the partner, however site by site correct execution of portion control remains a focus driving OI claims. For OI claims and elevated RWT, BTG continues to target the problematic sites. 

We are seeing spillages and crushed packaging as the \#1 recurring issue (45 instances) ‚Äî particularly for Wagamama, Dishoom, and Pho. Wrong items and improper cooking follow as the next most common complaint types. We have looked into this at brand level, this has also been shared with AMs but sharing for insight below: 

* **Wagamama** (35+ Issues): Main issue called out: (1) spilled food & sauce and (2) undercooked rice,  
* **Dishoom** (15+ Issues): Main issue called out: spilled and/or leaked curries  
* **Pho** (15+ Issues): Main issue called out: (1) spilled broth (2) incorrect or missing noodles  
* **PizzaExpress** (10+ Issues): Main issue called out: (1) wrong or undercooked pizza (2) Crushed box with toppings stuck to box  
* **Bill‚Äôs** (8 Issues): Main issue called out: (1) Crushed packaging (shepherd's pie), (2) incorrect or non-vegetarian substitutions  
* **Banana Tree** (5 Issues): Main issue called out: missing or incorrect main items  
* **Giggling Squid** (5 Issues): Main issue called out: (1) spillages, (2) undercooked food (3) incorrect items 

**Scheduled Order Deep Dive \[**[data](https://deliveroo.looker.com/explore/orders/orders?qid=I5PE1TGLQy2vV5vY7WgbQ0)**\]**  
*All data below is between Wk/Com 29th Sep \- Wed 22nd Oct)*

Since Wk/Com 29th Sep, 17% of orders have been scheduled. Wk/com 6th and 13th October scheduled orders increased to 19% of Dinneroo orders, but WTD (Mon 20th \- Wed 22nd), it is 16% of orders.  Scheduled orders B10s are \-4.57pp lower than ASAP Orders and Order ratings are 0.04pp higher on scheduled orders. RWT (-2.7pp) and OI (-0.49pp) perform better on scheduled orders vs. ASAP orders. There have been no rejected scheduled orders since Wk/Com 29th Sep. One scheduled order has been cancelled by PizzaExpress on the 20th Oct, caused by an out of stock issue on Lasagna due to an insufficient quantity being defrosted. The order was placed at 9:13, and accepted by the partner, but then cancelled at 16:30. The customer did not place a placement order that day, although placed another [Dinneroo order](https://admin.deliveroo.co.uk/admin/orders/50344271045), with Farmer J on the 23rd, and half the order was not handed over/collected by the rider.  

42 scheduled orders (0.29% of scheduled orders) have arrived more than 15min late. 43% of these 15min+ late orders were due to Rider late arrival, 19% were due to Restaurant delays, 10% were due to Rider and Restaurant delays and 29% were due to other issues, such as delays on route to customer. Improvements in Rider Supply will help improve the rider late to restaurant defects.  

Dinneroo Scheduled order‚Äôs B10s are \-6.15pp lower than Non-Dinneroo scheduled orders at the same time (0.7pp) and lower than B10s for Non-Dinneroo ASAP orders at the same time by \-6.15. 

Partner Ops will continue to monitor the performance of Scheduled orders with the approach that there is a much lower tolerance of defects on scheduled orders vs. ASAP. Further insights will continue to be provided periodically on the Dinneroo WBR.

* ### **New survey**: CX who **made a basket but didn‚Äôt place an order**, according to DS (Thank you [Chloe Hobson](mailto:chloe.hobson@deliveroo.co.uk)\!). **35 responses so far. We hope to run this again on Tuesday to capture next Monday‚Äôs drop-offs.**     **Insight so far (n=35):** 

  * **Over half (56%) said they went on to place an order in a later session.**  
  * 86% of those who didn‚Äôt place an order were either **‚Äòjust browsing‚Äô (13%)** or **planning to order some other time (73%)**.

  * This supports the hypothesis that:  
    * \[a\] Many drop-off Cx are not put off by the proposition.

#### B) AOV/meal size Deep dive follow up ([Polina Popova](mailto:polina.popova@deliveroo.co.uk))

This is a quick follow up for the previous deep dive focused on AOV and meal size of FTT meals. The insights are not actionable at this point, it aims at understanding how actual user behavior aligns with what we imagine it should be.

**3 main ideas:**

- Only 61% of orders are just FTT meal (+4% where user adds drink/dessert)  
- In 50% of orders customers spent roughly what they used to, in 25% they saved money and in 25% they spent more  
- 11% of orders were done by customers who are quite used to ordering in the FTT window (Mon \-Thu early evenings)

More details:

- In a previous meeting I have shown that there are many customers with order value more than ¬£25. I have bucketed orders into 5 buckets according to meal/party size:

  **61% \- Bucket 1 \-  just one FTT meal \- ¬£23.4 AOV**

    4% \- Bucket 2 \- FTT meal \+ drink/dessert \- ¬£29.4 AOV

  **26% \- Bucket 3 \- FTT meal \+ either 1-2 small plates or one extra main \- ¬£32.5 AOV**

    7% \- Bucket 4 \- 2 FTT meals or FTT meal \+ 2 mains etc \- ¬£49.9 AOV

    1% \- Bucket 5 \-  very large orders \- ¬£100.3 AOV

- We discussed 4 main hypothesis of why this can happen:

  1\) Gold Plus customers are encouraged to order above ¬£30

  2\) Some restaurants are better in upselling than others

  3\) May be family is just more than 4 people

  4\) They are not sure about the size or they want to have more leftovers for next day


We can look into the first 3 hypotheses with data we have, the 4th one is not possible to explore with data.   
 

- Gold plus customers‚Äô orders are indeed exceeding ¬£30 more frequently but this it is not having a major impact in overall picture:  
1)  The difference between the percentage of orders above vs. below ¬£30 is only 5 p.p. for Gold vs. not-Gold customers  
2) Only 20% of FTT orders are orders by Gold customers 

- Looking at restaurant level is a bit tricky at the moment because numbers are still too low. Nonetheless, most restaurants have roughly the same distribution of orders per bucket. Among top 5 there are two interesting cases with Bucket 1 being larger (74% vs 61%) and Bucket 3 being smaller:  
  - Pho: they have a very detailed menu where  customers choose specific meals for adults and kids in the FTT offer  
  - Banana Tree: all their FTT meals are ¬£20

		(those might not be the reasons, just potential reasons)

- Some families might just be larger. We can look at past user orders and compare them to FTT orders (only looking into EC):  
  - Comparing FTT order value vs  the customer‚Äôs AOV in 2025 (on order level):  
    - 50% of FTT orders are within \+-¬£5 of the customer‚Äôs AOV  
    - The rest of distribution is very symmetrical: 13% in each of 4 buckets: ¬£5-10, \>¬£10,  \-¬£10 to \-¬£5, \<-¬£10  
    - **Meaning that in 50% of orders customers spent their usual amount, in 25% saved money and in 25% spent more than usual**  
    - Logically, this differs per bucket. Percent of orders with customers spending their usual amount or saving:  
      - Bucket 1: 86%  
      - Bucket 3: 60%  
      - Bucket 5: only 3% so those are really one-off large orders  
  - Looking into number of customer‚Äôs orders in FTT timeframe (Mon-Thu evening, I tool slightly larger window) pre-FTT starting from June (so roughly 3 months):  
    - 0 orders: 25%  
    - 1-3 orders: 40%  
    - 4-10 orders: 25%  
    - \>10 orders: 11% \- **likely cannibalisation from the customer perspective**.
